title: Blocked Weighted Bootstrap — bbw
text: bootstrap technique described article. BBW used RAM S3M modification percentile bootstrap include blocking weighting account complex sample design. RAM S3M surveys, sample complex sense unweighted cluster sample. Data analysis procedures need account sample design. blocked weighted bootstrap (BBW) can used: Blocked - block corresponds primary sampling unit PSU = cluster. PSUs resampled replacement. Observations within resampled PSUs also sampled replacement. Weighted - RAM S3M samples use population proportional sampling (PPS) weight sample prior data collection (e.g. done SMART surveys). means posterior weighting procedure required. {bbw} uses "roulette wheel" algorithm weight (.e. population) selection probability PSUs bootstrap replicates. case prior weighting PPS clusters given weight. posterior weighting (RAM S3M) weight population PSU. procedure similar fitness proportionate selection technique used evolutionary computing. total m PSUs sampled replacement bootstrap replicate (m number PSUs survey sample). required statistic applied replicate. reported estimate consists 0.025th (95% LCL), 0.5th (point estimate), 0.975th (95% UCL) quantiles distribution statistic across survey replicates. Early versions {bbw} package resample observations within PSUs following: Cameron AC, Gelbach JB, Miller DL, Bootstrap-based improvements inference clustered errors, Review Economics Statistics, 2008:90;414–427 doi:10.1162/rest.90.3.414 used large number (e.g. 3999) survey replicates. Current versions {bbw} package resample observations within PSUs use smaller number survey replicates (e.g. n = 400). computationally efficient approach

title: Blocked Weighted Bootstrap — bootBW
code: # Example function - estimate a proportion for a binary (0/1) variable):  oneP <- function(x, params) {   v1 <- params[1]   v1Data <- x[[v1]]   oneP <- mean(v1Data, na.rm = TRUE)   return(oneP) }  # Example call to bootBW function using RAM-OP test data:  bootP <- bootBW(x = indicatorsHH,                 w = villageData,                 statistic = oneP,                 params = "anc1",                 outputColumns = "anc1",                 replicates = 9)  # Example estimate with 95% CI:  quantile(bootP, probs = c(0.500, 0.025, 0.975), na.rm = TRUE) #>       50%      2.5%     97.5%  #> 0.2196060 0.1959739 0.2593955

title: Recode — recode
text: Utility function recodes variables based user recode specifications. Handles numeric factor variables.

title: Recode — recode
code: recode(var, recodes, afr, anr = TRUE, levels)

title: Recode — recode
text: var Variable recode recodes Character string recode specifications: Recode specifications character string separated semicolons form input=output : "1=1;2=1;3:6=2;else=NA"   afr Return factor. Default TRUE var factor FALSE otherwise anr Coerce result numeric (default TRUE) levels Order levels returned factor; default use sort order level names.
code: \item If an input value satisfies more than one specification, then the first (reading from left to right) is applied  \item If no specification is satisfied, then the input value is carried over to the result unchanged  \item \code{NA} is allowed on both input and output  \item The following recode specifications are supported:      \tabular{lll}{       \strong{Specification} \tab \strong{Example}          \tab \strong{Notes}                                                 \cr       Single values          \tab \code{9=NA}               \tab                                                                \cr       Set of values          \tab \code{c(1,2,5)=1}         \tab The left-hand-side is any R function call that returns a vector\cr                              \tab \code{seq(1,9,2)='odd'}   \tab                                                                \cr                              \tab \code{1:10=1}             \tab                                                                \cr       Range of values        \tab \code{7:9=3}              \tab Special values \code{lo} and \code{hi} may be used             \cr                              \tab \code{lo:115=1}           \tab                                                                \cr       Other values           \tab \code{else=NA}            \tab     }  \item Character values are quoted as in :       \code{recodes = "c(1,2,5)='sanitary' else='unsanitary'"}  \item The output may be the (scalar) result of a function call as in:       \code{recodes = "999=median(var, na.rm = TRUE)"}  \item Users are advised to carefully check the results of \code{recode()} calls with any outputs that are the results of a function call.  \item The output may be the (scalar) value of a variable as in:       \code{recodes = "999=scalarVariable"}  \item If all of the output values are numeric, and if \code{'afr'} is \code{FALSE}, then a numeric result is returned; if \code{var} is a factor then (by default) so is the result.
